<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Glossmeter" class="currentChild" href="Glossmeter">Glossmeter</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A device used to measure the amount of <a title="Gloss" href="Gloss">gloss</a> possessed by a paper, expressed as the ratio of the amount of the paper sample's reflected light to the light falling on it as compared to a gloss standard (polished black glass) of 100 "gloss units." Gloss is measured at a determined angle from the paper's surface; for coated papers, it tends to be 15º from the paper's surface (for extremely glossy papers, best results can be obtained at 20º from the paper's surface). The glossmeter shines a light of known intensity on the paper and calculates the amount reflected back at the chosen angle of reflectance. Gloss can differ with <a title="Grain Direction" href="Grain_Direction">grain direction</a>, so readings in both the grain and <a title="Cross-Grain Direction" href="Cross-Grain_Direction">cross-grain direction</a> are typically taken. (See <a title="Gloss" href="Gloss">Gloss</a>.) 
</p>
